{
  "text": "Obesity represents the major risk factor for the development of insulin resistance in children and adolescents [CITATION_1] , and insulin resistance/hyperinsulinemia is believed to be an important link between obesity and the associated metabolic abnormalities and cardiovascular risk [CITATION_2] . Approximately, 55% of the variance in insulin sensitivity in children can be explained by total adiposity, after adjusting for other confounders, such as age, gender, ethnicity and pubertal stage [CITATION_3] . Obese children have hyperinsulinemia and peripheral insulin resistance with an w40% lower insulin-stimulated glucose metabolism than non-obese children [CITATION_4] . In a recent population-based study conducted in American adolescents, insulin resistance was detected in w 50% obese subjects [CITATION_5] and adiposity was also confirmed to be the most important factor affecting insulin sensitivity.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "31532854",
